<p><strong>The Age of Napoleon: Guided Reading Activity 18.3 Answer Key</strong></p>
<p><strong>Paragraph 1</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> What were Napoleon's early victories?</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Napoleon's early victories included the Battle of Lodi in 1796, which opened the way to Piedmont and Lombardy, and the Battle of Rivoli in 1797, which secured his control over the Italian Peninsula.</p>
<p><strong>Paragraph 2</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> How did Napoleon consolidate his power in France?</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Napoleon consolidated his power in France through a coup d'Ã©tat in November 1799, which established the Consulate with him as First Consul. He then introduced a new constitution (the Constitution of the Year VIII) that gave him sweeping powers, including the ability to name senators, appoint officials, and control the military.</p>
<p><strong>Paragraph 3</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> What were the key features of Napoleon's empire?</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Napoleon's empire was characterized by strong centralized control, the expansion of French territory through military conquests, and the establishment of a Napoleonic Code that standardized laws and abolished feudalism.</p>
<p><strong>Paragraph 4</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> How did the Napoleonic Wars impact Europe?</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The Napoleonic Wars had a significant impact on Europe, destabilizing existing political boundaries, contributing to the rise of nationalism, and leading to the reconfiguration of the European map at the Congress of Vienna in 1815.</p>
<p><strong>Paragraph 5</strong></p>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> What were the factors that led to Napoleon's downfall?</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Napoleon's downfall can be attributed to a combination of factors, including his disastrous invasion of Russia in 1812, the formation of an anti-French coalition, and the economic strain caused by the prolonged wars.</p>